message.content:
To begin, note that the first symbol the grammar can emit is always produced by the left‑hand child of the very first rule used for S.

S has only three possible first rules  
1. S → NT102 NT144  
2. S → NT29 NT61  
3. S → NT47 NT138  

Hence the first token of any sentence in the language must be the first terminal that NT102, NT29, or NT47 can generate.

• NT47 is immediate‑terminal: NT47 → 't26' | 't53'.  
  So a sentence derived through rule 3 must start with t26 or t53 – never t3.

• NT29 derives only through
  NT29 → NT160 NT160 | NT24 NT49 | NT77 NT77
  Examine the leftmost terminals obtainable from each left child:
  – NT160 → 't39' or NT172…, giving either t39 or t10 first.  
  – NT24 begins with NT13 or NT174; NT13 begins with NT121 (t59), NT35 (t43),
    or NT55 (t49/t24/t15); NT174 is 't64'.  
  – NT77 begins with t35 or, via NT155/NT22/NT99, with t35, t53, t78, … but never t3.  
  None of these possibilities yield t3 as the very first token.

• NT102 can be
  NT102 → 't43'     (first token t43)  
  NT102 → NT88 NT59
  In the second case NT88 is the left child.  But
  NT88 → 't77' | NT27 NT25 | NT127 NT28
  – Direct choice gives t77.  
  – NT27 starts with NT56, and NT56 begins with t53.  
  – NT127 is 't21'.  
  Thus NT88 can lead with t77, t53, or t21 – never t3.  
  Therefore NT102 can never start with t3.

Consequently, no derivation of S can yield a string whose very first token is t3.  
The target string begins with t3, so it cannot be generated by this grammar.

No

The start symbol S has only three possible productions:

1. S → NT102 NT144  
2. S → NT29 NT61  
3. S → NT47 NT138  

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form (no ε‑productions), the first terminal of any derived string must come from the left‑most leaf produced by the left‑most non‑terminal in the chosen production.

• For S → NT102 NT144  
  NT102 can derive either the single terminal t43 or a string that begins with NT88.  
  – If NT102 → t43, the derived string would begin with t43.  
  – If NT102 → NT88 NT59, the left‑most terminal still comes from NT88.  
    NT88 is either the single terminal t77 or starts with NT27, which in turn starts with NT56 → NT10 …, producing t53 as the first terminal.  
  Thus every derivation headed by NT102 begins with t43, t77, or t53—not t59.

• For S → NT47 NT138  
  NT47 is lexical and yields only t26 or t53.  
  Hence any string derived via this rule must begin with t26 or t53, never t59.

• For S → NT29 NT61  
  The left‑most terminal comes from NT29.  
  Examining every expansion of NT29 shows:  
  – NT29 → NT77 NT77  ( NT77 begins with t35, t77, t53 … but never t59 )  
  – NT29 → NT160 NT160 ( NT160 begins with t39 or t10 )  
  – NT29 → NT24 NT49.  For the left‑most path NT24 → NT13 NT171, we get NT13 → NT121 NT90; NT121 is the sole producer of t59, so this is the only place where NT59 could appear first.  
    However NT90 must then produce the next token (t34).  NT90’s only possibilities are  
      • NT28 NT129, which begins with t39, or  
      • NT93 NT149, which begins with t53.  
    Neither matches t34.  All other expansions of NT24 start with t64 (NT174) or t26/t53 (NT47) and thus also fail to match t59.

Consequently, no derivation from S can yield a string whose first terminal is t59.  
The given string begins with t59, so it is impossible to generate it with this grammar.

The start symbol S has only three productions:

1. S → NT102 NT144  
2. S → NT29 NT61  
3. S → NT47 NT138  

For the given string to be generated, its final (45‑th) token “t14” must be produced by the second non‑terminal of whichever of these three alternatives is chosen, because none of the grammar’s rules delete symbols (the grammar is in Chomsky normal form and contains no ε‑productions).

• If S → NT47 NT138 were used, the last token would have to come from NT138.  
 NT138 is a lexical rule: NT138 → 't43'.  
 Hence the last token would be “t43”, not “t14”.  
 Impossible.

• If S → NT102 NT144 were used, the last token would have to come from NT144.  
 NT144 has exactly one production: NT144 → NT118 NT12, and NT12 → 't28'.  
 Therefore any string derived from NT144 ends with “t28”, not “t14”.  
 Impossible.

• If S → NT29 NT61 were used, the last token would have to come from NT61.  
 NT61 has exactly one production: NT61 → NT112 NT85, so its last token must come from NT85.  
 NT85 → NT92 NT71, so the last token must come from NT71.  
 NT71 → NT141 NT100, so the last token must come from NT100.  
 The only possibilities for NT100 are  
  NT100 → NT134 NT17 or NT100 → NT48 NT33.  
 Thus the last token must come from NT17 or NT33.  
 NT33 is lexical 't70'; NT17 ultimately derives either NT78 NT93 or NT2 NT24, and none of the lexical rules reachable from those non‑terminals produce “t14”.  
 Hence NT61 can never yield a string ending in “t14”.  
 Impossible.

Since none of the three possible expansions of the start symbol can produce a string whose final token is “t14”, the given 45‑token string cannot be generated by the grammar.
